Social Change: The Lived Experiences of Black Women Educators as Diverse Leaders in Classrooms -- tTheme Three Reimagined Realities -- tIntroduction -- t12 Principals and Reconciliation Education in Saskatchewan Schools: Challenges, Opportunities, and Supports -- t13 In a Paradigm of Belonging: Leadership Practices in a Context of Systemic Inequality -- t14 Standing as Accomplices: Becoming Diversity Leaders -- t15 Black School Leaders in Low-Income Urban Ontario Schools: Striving for Social Justice -- t16 Black Leadership and Role of Spirituality and Community -- t17 nîkânastamâkêwin: Leading Indigenous Initiatives in (Colonial) Universities -- tConclusion: Embedding Practices of Social Justice -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWidely understood to be the best tool of social change, education offers a space to interrogate persistent and damaging oppressions, calling into question the cultural and political antecedents, as well as the current politics and practices, that have facilitated inequity. Educational leaders themselves, however, have much to learn about dismantling systems that maintain these barriers.Diversity Leadership in Education offers a deep look into the complexities and opportunities afforded by new models of diversity leadership. Authors from across North America explore how diverse leaders are key to improving the school experience for marginalized students. Indigenous, Black, racialized, and collaborative forms of leadership contribute to decolonizing educational settings by unsettling hegemonic ideas; these include the dominance of equity myths in educational administration and pedagogical whitewashing around issues germane to social justice.Unpacking privilege in education systems, the volume speaks to incorporating social justice in everyday leadership practices through advocacy, solidarity, spirituality, relationality, and reconciliation. It profiles diversity leadership as a rudder, steering a more inclusive and equitable society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aDiversity in the workplacezCanada. 0aDiversity in the workplace-Canada. 0aEducational leadershipzCanada. 0aEducational leadership-Canada. 0aSocial justicezCanada. 0aSocial justice-Canada. 7aEDUCATION / Administration / Higher.2bisacsh  a#Metoo.  aBlack Lives Matter.  aIndigenization.  aadvocacy.  aallyship.  abarriers.  acommunity.  acritical race theory.  acultural practices.  adouble consciousness.  aequity.  aethnicity.  agender.  ahegemonic leadership.  ainequity.  aintersectionality.  aoppressed.  aperformativity.  aprivilege.  arace.  areconciliation.  arelationality.  asocial justice.  asolidarity.  aspirituality.1 aAgger-Gupta, Niels, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlphonse, Shirley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAntoine, Asma-na-hi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeaton, Terri-Lynne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBedi, Shailoo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBedi, Shailoo, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBoomen, Karyn Vanden, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aButler, Alana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCampbell, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCappello, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChan, Adrienne S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChowdhari Tremblay, Reeta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voca